				\begin{document}$${\rm{\Delta }}{\rm{P}}={\rm{P}}^{\prime} \mbox{--}{\rm{P}}=({\rm{n}}+{\rm{\Delta }}{\rm{n}}).({\rm{I}}+{\rm{\Delta }})\mbox{--}{\rm{n}}.{\rm{I}}={\rm{\Delta }}{\rm{n}}.{\rm{I}}+{\rm{n}}.{\rm{\Delta }}{\rm{I}}+{\rm{\Delta }}{\rm{n}}.{\rm{\Delta }}I$$\end{document}ΔP=P′–P=(n+Δn).(I+Δ)–n.I=Δn.I+n.ΔI+Δn.ΔIP′ is the precipitation under 2 °C conditions, and P, n, and I are the parameters under 1.5 °C conditions; Δ represents the change between 1.5 °C and 2 °C climates. Here, the Δn.I term represents the change due to the frequency change and n.ΔI represents the change due to the intensity change. Δn.I and n.ΔI will be called the frequency term and intensity term from now on30. This decomposition was conducted for precipitation larger than 1 mm/day (i.e., precipitation during wet days) in warming scenarios 1.5 °C and 2 °C. For dry spells, we can replace P with the total dry days (D) and I is equal to the mean DSL. We found that the covariance term was negligible during our analysis (Fig. S3).
